<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Dryer" class="currentChild" href="Dryer">Dryer</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
In <a title="Web Offset Lithography" href="Web_Offset_Lithography">web offset lithography</a> (or other type of web printing), an oven through which the printed web passes. The dryer—operating at a temperature of up to 600ºF, heats the web itself to a temperature of about 330ºF. Most <a title="Blanket-to-Blanket Press" href="Blanket-to-Blanket_Press">blanket-to-blanket press</a>es require <a title="Floating Dryer" href="Floating_Dryer">floating dryer</a>s, as the web has ink on both sides. A dryer is needed when printing with <a title="Heatset Ink" href="Heatset_Ink">heatset ink</a>s which dry and set only with the application of heat. Most dryers are either <a title="Open-Flame Dryer" href="Open-Flame_Dryer">open-flame dryer</a>s or <a title="High-Velocity Hot-Air Dryer" href="High-Velocity_Hot-Air_Dryer">high-velocity hot-air dryer</a>s. There are also combination open-flame, medium-velocity hot-air dryers. After drying, the web needed to pass through the cooled <a title="chill rolls" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/chill_rolls">chill rolls</a>. 
</p>
